<h1>Bramley Golf Club</h1>
<p style="font-size:14pt;color:#555;font-weight:bold;margin:2pt 0;">Continuous Improvement Programme</p>
<p style="font-size:13pt;color:#c0392b;font-weight:bold;margin:2pt 0 4pt;">System Continuity Guide — What to do if the developer is unavailable</p>
<p style="font-size:10pt;color:#888;font-style:italic;">Prepared by John de Wit &nbsp;|&nbsp; June 2026 &nbsp;|&nbsp; For: Club Chairman and Club Manager</p>

<hr>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Why this document exists</strong><br><br>
The CIP system was built and is maintained by John de Wit, a club member. This document tells you everything you need to know to keep the system running, deal with problems, and — if necessary — hand it to someone else. You do not need a technical background to follow these instructions.<br><br>
Keep this document somewhere safe and accessible. It contains no passwords (for security reasons) but tells you exactly where everything lives and who to contact.
</div>

<div class="toc">
<p class="toc-title">Contents</p>
<p>1. What the system is and where it runs</p>
<p>2. The accounts you need access to</p>
<p>3. Day-to-day operation — what runs automatically</p>
<p>4. What the Club Manager can do without a developer</p>
<p>5. What requires a developer</p>
<p>6. If the system stops working</p>
<p>7. Emergency data recovery</p>
<p>8. Finding a replacement developer</p>
<p>9. Handing the system over</p>
<p>10. Summary — the one-page version</p>
</div>

<hr>

<h2>1. What the system is and where it runs</h2>
<p>The CIP is a web application. It runs entirely in the cloud — there is no server in the clubhouse, no local computer involved, and nothing that needs to be switched on or maintained physically.</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>Component</th><th>What it is</th><th>Where it is</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>The application</strong></td><td>The website members and directors use</td><td>Vercel (cloud hosting)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>The database</strong></td><td>All submissions, scores, members, config</td><td>Neon (cloud database)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>The code</strong></td><td>The source files that make the app work</td><td>GitHub (code repository)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Email sending</strong></td><td>Sends emails to members and directors</td><td>Resend (email service)</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>AI scoring</strong></td><td>The intelligence behind the scoring</td><td>Anthropic Claude API</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The website address is: <strong>https://bramley-bci.vercel.app</strong> (or the custom domain if one has been configured).</p>

<p>The system runs two automatic tasks every week:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Monday 07:00</strong> — scores all new member submissions and emails directors</li>
  <li><strong>Sunday 06:00</strong> — emails a data backup to the Club Manager</li>
</ul>

<h2>2. The accounts you need access to</h2>
<p>Five online accounts keep the system alive. Credentials should be stored securely in the club's password manager or a sealed envelope kept by the Secretary.</p>

<h3>GitHub — github.com</h3>
<p><strong>What for:</strong> Stores all the code and documentation. The repository is <code>johnnydw-bit/BCI</code>.</p>
<p><strong>What you can do here:</strong> Read documentation, download files, invite a new developer to collaborate.</p>
<p><strong>If lost:</strong> A new developer can fork the code and continue independently.</p>

<h3>Vercel — vercel.com</h3>
<p><strong>What for:</strong> Hosts the website and runs the automatic weekly tasks.</p>
<p><strong>Critical:</strong> The following secret values ("environment variables") are stored here and are required for the app to function:</p>
<ul>
  <li>DATABASE_URL — connects to the database</li>
  <li>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY — connects to the AI scoring service</li>
  <li>RESEND_API_KEY — connects to the email service</li>
  <li>MANAGER_EMAIL — the Club Manager's email for alerts and backups</li>
  <li>EMAIL_FROM — the sending email address</li>
  <li>NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL — the website address</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>If lost:</strong> The app stops working. The database (Neon) is separate, so data is safe, but the app needs to be redeployed with the correct values above.</p>

<h3>Neon — neon.tech</h3>
<p><strong>What for:</strong> The database. Contains every submission, score, director record, config value, and audit trail.</p>
<p><strong>This is where all the data lives.</strong> Even if everything else fails, the data here is safe as long as this account is intact.</p>
<p><strong>If lost:</strong> A new database can be created and all data restored from a JSON backup file.</p>

<h3>Resend — resend.com</h3>
<p><strong>What for:</strong> Sends all emails to members and directors.</p>
<p><strong>If lost:</strong> Emails stop sending. The app still works; members and directors just won't receive notifications. A new Resend account can be set up quickly.</p>

<h3>Anthropic — console.anthropic.com</h3>
<p><strong>What for:</strong> The AI that scores submissions and generates member emails.</p>
<p><strong>If lost:</strong> The scoring process stops working. The app's data and the member portal still work. A new API key from a new account restores full function.</p>

<div class="action-now">
<strong>Action recommended now — while John is available:</strong><br>
Ask John to add the Club Manager as a collaborator on the Vercel project and the GitHub repository. This costs nothing and means you have direct access without needing John's personal login credentials.
</div>

<h2>3. Day-to-day operation — what runs automatically</h2>
<p>In normal circumstances, the system requires <strong>no human intervention</strong>.</p>

<table>
  <tr><th>When</th><th>What happens automatically</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Monday 07:00</strong></td><td>New submissions are scored; directors receive email reports; high-scoring items (9+/10) trigger immediate alerts; H&amp;S items are flagged to the Club Manager</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Sunday 06:00</strong></td><td>A CSV data backup is emailed to the Club Manager</td></tr>
</table>

<p>The only regular human tasks are:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Directors review the triage report at their convenience after Monday morning</li>
  <li>Club Manager acts on submissions — changing statuses, setting target dates, assigning owners</li>
  <li>Club Manager periodically downloads a full JSON backup (Admin → Setup → Full backup) and stores it somewhere safe</li>
</ul>

<h2>4. What the Club Manager can do without a developer</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Task</th><th>Where in the app</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Add or remove directors</td><td>Admin → Directors</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Reset a director's PIN</td><td>Admin → Directors → Edit → Reset PIN</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Change scoring weights and thresholds</td><td>Admin → Scoring Config</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Change email tone and sign-off name</td><td>Admin → Communications</td></tr>
  <tr><td>View dashboard statistics</td><td>Admin → Dashboard</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Download a full data backup</td><td>Admin → Setup → Full backup (JSON)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Restore submissions from a CSV backup</td><td>Admin → Setup → Restore from CSV</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Run the triage scoring manually</td><td>Admin → Setup → Run triage now</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Add new database columns after an update</td><td>Admin → Setup → Initialise database</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>5. What requires a developer</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Task</th><th>Difficulty</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Adding a new feature to the app</td><td>Medium–High</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Changing which categories exist</td><td>Low — a code change and redeploy</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Adding a new director role</td><td>Low — a code change and redeploy</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Changing the AI scoring approach</td><td>Low — a code change and redeploy</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Fixing a bug or error</td><td>Low–Medium depending on the issue</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Setting up a custom domain name</td><td>Low</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Upgrading to a paid hosting tier</td><td>Low — account change only</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Restoring from a full JSON backup if the app is down</td><td>Low — run a script (see Section 7)</td></tr>
</table>
<p>For the restore script specifically, any technically competent person with Node.js installed can run it without understanding the rest of the code.</p>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h2>6. If the system stops working</h2>

<h3>The app shows a blank page or error</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Wait 5 minutes and try again — Vercel occasionally has brief hiccups</li>
  <li>If it persists, log in to Vercel (vercel.com) and check the deployment status and error logs</li>
  <li>If the errors mention "database" or "column does not exist" — a code update was deployed without running the database initialisation. If a director can still sign in, run: <strong>Admin → Setup → Initialise database</strong></li>
  <li>If you cannot log in at all, try opening the browser console (press F12, click Console) and paste:<br>
  <code>fetch('/api/admin/init-db', {method:'POST'}).then(r=>r.json()).then(console.log)</code><br>
  This only works if a director session is still active in that browser.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Emails have stopped arriving</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Check the Resend dashboard for delivery errors</li>
  <li>Check the RESEND_API_KEY in Vercel's environment variables is still valid</li>
  <li>Check the free tier limit hasn't been reached (100 emails/day on the free tier)</li>
</ol>

<h3>The scoring (triage) is failing</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Check the Anthropic dashboard for API errors or billing issues</li>
  <li>Check the ANTHROPIC_API_KEY in Vercel's environment variables is still valid</li>
  <li>The AI has usage costs — check the account is funded</li>
</ol>

<h2>7. Emergency data recovery</h2>

<h3>What backups exist</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Backup type</th><th>How often</th><th>Where</th></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>CSV backup</strong></td><td>Automatically every Sunday</td><td>Emailed to Club Manager</td></tr>
  <tr><td><strong>Full JSON backup</strong></td><td>On demand — download from Admin → Setup</td><td>Wherever you saved it</td></tr>
</table>

<div class="warning">
<strong>Important:</strong> The JSON backup is far more complete than the CSV. It includes every table — submissions, scores, clusters, audit trail, config, and directors. Store JSON backups somewhere safe <em>outside</em> the app — email them to yourself, save to a USB drive, or upload to OneDrive or Google Drive.
</div>

<h3>If data is corrupted or accidentally deleted (app is still working)</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <strong>Admin → Setup → Restore from CSV</strong> and upload the most recent CSV backup</li>
  <li>This restores submission records — it updates or inserts without deleting anything</li>
</ol>

<h3>If the database is lost or destroyed (full recovery)</h3>
<p>You need:</p>
<ul>
  <li>A full JSON backup file</li>
  <li>A computer with Node.js installed</li>
  <li>The DATABASE_URL from the Neon account</li>
</ul>
<p>Steps:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Create a new database in Neon if the old one is gone</li>
  <li>Open a terminal in the project folder (or ask a developer to do steps 3–4)</li>
  <li>Run: <code>node scripts/restore.js path\to\your-backup.json</code></li>
  <li>The script reconnects all the data and prints a summary</li>
</ol>
<p>A developer can complete this in under 30 minutes with a recent backup.</p>

<h2>8. Finding a replacement developer</h2>

<h3>What to tell a new developer</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Stack:</strong> Next.js 15, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS, hosted on Vercel</li>
  <li><strong>Database:</strong> PostgreSQL via Neon (serverless)</li>
  <li><strong>AI:</strong> Anthropic Claude (claude-sonnet for scoring, claude-haiku for emails)</li>
  <li><strong>Email:</strong> Resend</li>
  <li><strong>Repo:</strong> github.com/johnnydw-bit/BCI (private)</li>
  <li><strong>Docs:</strong> Full documentation in the <code>docs/</code> folder of the repository</li>
</ul>

<h3>What to give a new developer</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Access to the GitHub repository</li>
  <li>Access to the Vercel project</li>
  <li>Access to the Neon database</li>
  <li>This document and the committee guide</li>
  <li>A recent full JSON backup</li>
  <li>The environment variable values from Vercel</li>
</ul>

<h3>Cost of the system</h3>
<table>
  <tr><th>Service</th><th>Current tier</th><th>Monthly cost</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Vercel</td><td>Free (Hobby)</td><td>£0</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Neon</td><td>Free</td><td>£0</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Anthropic</td><td>Pay-per-use</td><td>~£2–£10</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Resend</td><td>Free (3,000 emails/month)</td><td>£0</td></tr>
  <tr><td>GitHub</td><td>Free</td><td>£0</td></tr>
  <tr><td colspan="2"><strong>Total</strong></td><td><strong>~£2–£10/month</strong></td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Where to find a developer</h3>
<ul>
  <li><strong>First:</strong> Ask among club members — there may be someone with relevant skills</li>
  <li><strong>Local:</strong> A local web development agency or freelancer</li>
  <li><strong>Online:</strong> Upwork, Toptal, or Codementor — search "Next.js developer"</li>
  <li><strong>Estimated cost:</strong> £50–£150/hour; the system is well-documented and minimal time is needed for routine updates</li>
</ul>

<h2>9. Handing the system over</h2>

<h3>Step 1 — Transfer the code repository</h3>
<p>In GitHub: Settings → Danger Zone → Transfer ownership. Transfer <code>BCI</code> to the new developer's GitHub account, or to a club-owned GitHub organisation.</p>

<h3>Step 2 — Transfer the Vercel project</h3>
<p>Add the new developer as a team member on the Vercel project, or redeploy under their account with the same environment variables.</p>

<h3>Step 3 — Transfer the Neon database</h3>
<p>Add the new developer as a collaborator, or provide the DATABASE_URL connection string.</p>

<h3>Step 4 — Transfer Resend and Anthropic accounts</h3>
<p>Add the new developer, or let them set up their own accounts and update the API keys in Vercel.</p>

<h3>Step 5 — Test everything</h3>
<p>After transfer: run Initialise Database, seed test data, run a manual triage, verify emails are sending.</p>

<div class="page-break"></div>

<h2>10. Summary — the one-page version</h2>

<div class="summary-box">
<h3 style="margin-top:0">The system runs itself</h3>
<p>Triage happens every Monday. Backups are emailed every Sunday. Directors review the report and make decisions. The Club Manager acts through the Admin panel. No IT involvement needed for routine operation.</p>
</div>

<h3>If something goes wrong — in order</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Wait a few minutes and try again</li>
  <li>Log in to Admin and run <strong>"Initialise database"</strong></li>
  <li>Check the Vercel dashboard for error messages</li>
  <li>Check Anthropic and Resend accounts for billing or quota issues</li>
  <li>If data is lost — restore from the JSON backup using the restore script</li>
  <li>Call a developer</li>
</ol>

<h3>The essential checklist — do these now, while John is available</h3>
<ul class="checklist">
  <li>Login credentials for Vercel, Neon, GitHub, Resend, and Anthropic stored securely</li>
  <li>Club Manager added as a Vercel collaborator</li>
  <li>Club Manager added as a GitHub collaborator</li>
  <li>A recent full JSON backup stored outside the app (email, USB, cloud storage)</li>
  <li>This document stored somewhere accessible to Chairman and Club Manager</li>
  <li>John's personal contact details recorded separately</li>
</ul>

<h3>Finding help</h3>
<p>The codebase is clean, well-documented, and uses standard modern technologies. Any competent Next.js developer can pick it up. The <code>docs/</code> folder in the GitHub repository contains all user and technical documentation.</p>

<div class="tip">
<strong>Remember:</strong> Even in an emergency, a quick call or message to John is almost always the fastest resolution. This document is for the scenario where that isn't possible.
</div>

<hr>
